Ha, fair enough — you're the Kafka admin, so Step 3 is on you. Let me give you the broker-side investigation properly then, since that's the real root cause, not the Connect probes.

What the broker logs already tell us: broker-2 (`172.16.8.137`, later `172.16.9.232` — note the **IP changed**, meaning the pod was rescheduled/restarted) dropped, and the Connect workers couldn't reach it. The brokers now show `0` restarts at 16h age — so they were all restarted ~16h ago, around the same time as the disconnect. That's the thing to explain: why did the brokers restart 16h ago?

Start here, in order:

Check why broker-2 (and the others) restarted. The pods are 16h old with 0 restarts now, meaning the restart count reset — they were recreated, not just bounced. Look at what the operator did:

```
oc get pods -n dev-kafka -l strimzi.io/cluster=dev-kafka-cluster -o wide
oc describe pod dev-kafka-cluster-broker-2 -n dev-kafka | grep -iE "started|created|node:|reason"
```

The `-o wide` shows which worker node each broker lands on. If brokers moved nodes 16h ago, a node drained/rebooted — that's your trigger.

Check the broker's own logs around the restart for the cause (OOM, liveness, rolling update):

```
oc logs dev-kafka-cluster-broker-2 -n dev-kafka --previous 2>/dev/null | tail -50
oc get events -n dev-kafka --sort-by=.lastTimestamp | grep -iE "broker-2|OOM|Killed|Unhealthy|Preempt|Evict" | tail -30
```

`--previous` gives you the pre-restart container log — that's where an OOMKilled or liveness-probe-kill will show.

Rule out the cluster operator doing a rolling restart. Strimzi rolls brokers for cert renewal, config changes, or Kafka version updates. Check the operator log for what it did 16h ago:

```
oc logs -n dev-kafka -l name=strimzi-cluster-operator --since=20h | grep -iE "roll|restart|broker-2|reconcil" | tail -40
```

Check node health — your earlier NTP work is a prime suspect. Kafka and TLS are clock-sensitive, and you'd flagged planned NTP remediation. If a node's clock jumped or a node rebooted for NTP/patching 16h ago, brokers on it would restart and TLS handshakes (the `9091`/`9093` disconnects in the cruise-control and Connect logs) would briefly fail:

```
oc get nodes -o wide
oc adm top nodes
oc get events --all-namespaces --sort-by=.lastTimestamp | grep -iE "NodeNotReady|Reboot|NTP|clock|Rebooted" | tail -20
```

The cruise-control angle. CC has 392 restarts and was hammering `node -1 disconnected` against the bootstrap `9091` in that log. That's CC unable to reach brokers during the same window. High CC restart counts over 78d aren't necessarily the incident, but if CC is crash-looping it adds noise and load. Worth checking its restart cadence:

```
oc get pod -n dev-kafka -l app.kubernetes.io/name=cruise-control -o jsonpath='{.items[0].status.containerStatuses[0].restartCount}{"\n"}'
oc logs -n dev-kafka -l app.kubernetes.io/name=cruise-control --since=20h | grep -iE "error|exception|disconnect" | tail -30
```

The likely story, given your environment: a node rebooted or had NTP remediation ~16h ago → broker-2's pod was rescheduled (hence the IP change 172.16.8.137 → 172.16.9.232) → during the few minutes the broker was unreachable, Connect's `/health` failed and the kubelet restarted the Connect pods, and CC threw its disconnect storm. Everything recovered once broker-2 came back. If that's confirmed, it's expected fallout from planned node/NTP work, not a Kafka fault — and the only durable hardening on the Connect side is the liveness-probe tuning so the next planned reboot doesn't bounce Connect.

One thing worth confirming as admin: were these brokers supposed to restart 16h ago? If you or the OCP admin did node patching / NTP work in that window, this is explained and benign. If nobody touched the nodes, then a broker restarting unprompted is the real ticket — check for OOMKilled in the `--previous` log and `oc adm top` for memory pressure on the dev workers.

